      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Need in the Subway</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Herb Gordon letter, commenting on June 3 editorial, says bathrooms in New York City subway stations that are now only for the use of transit employees should be made available to all, as they once were</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your June 3 editorial ''Public Necessities,'' you note that ''it is a disgrace that there are so few public bathrooms and that New York City officials have failed to build any new pay toilets for public use despite years of debate.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your June 3 editorial ''Public Necessities,'' you note that ''it is a disgrace that there are so few public bathrooms and that New York City officials have failed to build any new pay toilets for public use despite years of debate.''</p>
        <p>But as every subway rider knows, many public toilets in our subway stations have long been closed to general use, though we have all seen the locked doors opened for the private use of subway employees. Obviously, the toilets still function.</p>
        <p>Why are these toilets not reopened to the general public?</p>
        <p>HERB GORDON  New York, June 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
